    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_174320245" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/174320245" />
    <a title="Geoff Sebesta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4280880-geoff-sebesta"><img alt="Geoff Sebesta" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/174320245?book_show_action=true">Jun 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Geoff Sebesta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Geoff Sebesta" href="/user/show/4280880-geoff-sebesta">Geoff Sebesta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4280880-geoff-sebesta?shelf=good-books-about-france">good-books-about-france</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer174320245" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3017309912643862680">An interesting little chunk of history here. Burke wrote a towering condemnation of the constitutional monarchy of Revolutionary France. If you are saying &quot;I didn&apos;t know there was a constitutional monarchy in Revolutionary France&quot; that&apos;s because it didn&apos;t last very long. This is an extremely contemporary account. It does not extend much to either side. So if you want to know a lot about 1790 from the point of view of a British royalist, read this book. But if you want to know about 1791 or any o</span>
  <span id="freeText3017309912643862680" style="display:none">An interesting little chunk of history here. Burke wrote a towering condemnation of the constitutional monarchy of Revolutionary France. If you are saying "I didn't know there was a constitutional monarchy in Revolutionary France" that's because it didn't last very long. This is an extremely contemporary account. It does not extend much to either side. So if you want to know a lot about 1790 from the point of view of a British royalist, read this book. But if you want to know about 1791 or any other point of view, look elsewhere.<br /><br />So this is a technical takedown of the constitutional monarchy of Louis XVI...something like a building code inspector's report on a building that's already on fire. Burke is, shockingly to the modern reader, an avowed and eloquent monarchist, and spends much of his time here defending the concept of the constitutional regent. He doesn't think there's anything divine about kings, he just thinks they're a good idea and he explains why. It's heavy reading, difficult going. He really liked the word "antient." I guess he was trying to avoid confusion with "ancien" which was a very important word at this time. Or maybe he's just a british senator who's been dead for hundreds of years and that's really how they talked. His sympathies are clear; more than once he mentions that there was no reason for the French Revolution, since the country had been at peace for five years...and he says the army mutinied because malignant philosophers had taught them dangerous learnings. Seriously, sir? I don't think 18th century military units often mutiny because of "teaching" and "learning." It was probably because they were starving to death. You'd think in all that 1790 he'd read a newspaper. <br /><br />All in all Burke comes across as a competent representative of Dickens's "That Which Is."<br /><br />But the technicalities become entrancing. Burke was a contemporary conservative critic and a lot of what he said about the technical side of government (what the powers and responsibilities of a judiciary are, how military officers should be selected, et cetera) is very new to me and very interesting. His respect for tradition and wisdom is....excruciating. But reliable. His horror of revolutionary innovention has certainly been the fuel for a lot of comedy. I don't believe "antient" was ever a common word. I think he was just a guy in a wig who really talked like that. His cluelessness about the intolerability of conditions that lead to the Revolution counts against him, I think. But he made some good points.<br /><br />Good points include: the citizens treated France as roughly as the Mongols ever treated any tributary. Concentration of all power in the legislative was a mistake. Their system of dividing the country was ridiculous. An independent judiciary seems like a very useful tidebreak for a wave of legislative ideas. There was no point in keeping the King around (and in fact they didn't). The government had no way to compel obedience in the provinces but philosophy and force (and indeed that's what they used). And yes, it would all end in tears somehow.<br /><br /><br />I came here to write a review and now I'm reviewing the reviewers. I want to say, based on my growing store of knowledge about the French revolution, that Burke was no prophet. Although he accurately foresaw calamity for the French political system of 1790, guess what, it was not hard to see. From the modern perspective it's harder to believe that it took so long for disaster to strike. Burke didn't predict Napoleon, didn't predict WWII, didn't even predict that Louis XVI would lose his head, something that happened about eighteen months after he put this letter in the mail. And to everyone who is trying to stretch this to cover Obama...I guess when you only have two facts to rub together you do what you can, but come on. Reading history for prophecy is a chump move. Burke has more to tell you about the past than the future.<br /><br />According to Wikipedia this guy was the founder of modern conservativism or something. I can see that. Excellent at divining conflicts in abstract systems, excellent at ignoring inconvenient facts and missing giant dealbreakers like "hey the country is starving to death." I might read a bit more by him, it'd be interesting to see what he said about the American Revolution.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3017309912643862680" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


