    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_673683985" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/673683985" />
    <a title="J.A.A. Purves" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5452156-j-a-a-purves"><img alt="J.A.A. Purves" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1375234907p2/5452156.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/673683985?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.A.A. Purves" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.A.A. Purves" href="/user/show/5452156-j-a-a-purves">J.A.A. Purves</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5452156-j-a-a-purves?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5452156-j-a-a-purves?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer673683985" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17427841264542510020">This is a powerful work. And there is no way to fully appreciate it without paying attention to when it was written. The storming of the Bastille occurred in July of 1789 with the &quot;Declaration of the Rights of Man&quot; being published in August of 1789. Burke started writing this in 1789 and it was finally published in November of 1790.<br/><br/>This is before the death of Mirabeau and the National Assembly&apos;s legislation against the émigrés. It was before Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette were murdered. It was b</span>
  <span id="freeText17427841264542510020" style="display:none">This is a powerful work. And there is no way to fully appreciate it without paying attention to when it was written. The storming of the Bastille occurred in July of 1789 with the "Declaration of the Rights of Man" being published in August of 1789. Burke started writing this in 1789 and it was finally published in November of 1790.<br /><br />This is before the death of Mirabeau and the National Assembly's legislation against the émigrés. It was before Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette were murdered. It was before the dissolution of the Assembly, before the creation of the "Committee of Public Safety" and before the "Reign of Terror" in 1793 and 1794. It was before Napoleon's military coup in 1799. And yet, Burke predicts and tragically warns against all of these things.<br /><br />It's almost eerie how accurate his predictions were. And yet, while his writing is both passionate and elegant, it is laid out in careful reasoned argument. Burke possessed a political philosophy. The French Revolutionaries possessed an opposing political philosophy to Burke's. Burke argues that there are real world consequences to their ideas and reforms. What turn out to be tragic prophecies are reasoned predictions based on philosophy. (Remember, this is years before Thomas Jefferson begins to have doubts and regrets about supporting the French Revolution.)<br /><br />With historical hindsight, it is easy for us to say that Burke's 'Reflections' makes Thomas Paine's attempt to refute him in the 'Rights of Man' look childish by comparison. But, it's not that Burke was historically lucky. Instead, if it is true that the enactment of political philosophy into the real world produces necessary and sometimes even unintended consequences, then it takes a very wise and careful statesman to see this in advance. As rare as they are, Burke was such a statesman. Unfortunately, many of his predictions and warnings here have both (a) been proven true historically more than once, and (b) are even now still being ignored.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17427841264542510020" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

